value.def: An ace is a playing card with a single symbol on it. In most card games, the ace of a particular suit has either the highest or the lowest value of the cards in that suit.
If you describe someone such as a sports player as an ace, you mean that they are very good at what they do.

example.tran: 前一流赛车手斯特林·莫斯
王牌恐怖片制片人劳伦斯·伍尔西

gramarinfo.label: usu with supp, oft n N

value.tran: （在运动等方面）成绩超群的人，佼佼者

value.def: If you say that something is ace, you think that it is good and you like it a lot.
In tennis, an ace is a serve which is so fast that the other player cannot reach the ball.

example.ex: The American served three aces in the opening game of the set.
example.tran: 这位美国选手在该盘首局有三次发球直得。

value.def: If you say that someone holds all the aces, you mean that they have all the advantages in a contest or situation.

example.ex: 'When I was an adolescent,' says a thirty-one-year-old man, 'I thought girls held all the aces.'
example.tran: “当我还是个毛头小伙儿时，”一个31岁的男人说，“我觉得完全是女孩子说了算。”

value.tran: 占绝对优势；占尽天时地利人和

value.def: Something that is an ace in the hole is an advantage which you have over an opponent or rival, and which you can use if necessary.

example.ex: Our superior technology is our ace in the hole.
example.tran: 我们超众的技术是我们的法宝。

value.tran: 秘藏的王牌;应急的绝招;锦囊妙计

value.def: If you come within an ace of doing something, or you are within an ace of doing something, you very nearly do or experience it.

example.ex: He was intent on murder and he came within an ace of succeeding.
example.tran: 他一心想杀人并且差点就得逞了。
